@RyanHowells1 I don’t think it’s a good idea to be isolated in outpatients overnight especially given that many patients are intoxicated. 

Does depend a little on the local geographic set up though. 

I think I would ask for a lone worker risk assessment….

@BellaRoscetti @Not4Twos Two words 

‘Crack on’ 

Then leave doing what you said you were going to do in the first place.

@maddoggie2 @sandycann2 Patches in the mouth could be cancer- we see precipitous weight loss in oral cancers both pre but especially post treatment. 
I expect all patients to have a current weight in their notes. 
I might not expect it pre diagnosis, but it’s not ridiculously off piste.

@clarkesince91 I was asked to stay late to call micro about a fungal nail infection and systemic treatment for a patient. 

Figured that was fairly safely a tomorrow job. 

I didn’t stay late very often as a foundation dr.

@eilidh_garrett @JonnyGucks I can send you photos of the Cancers chopped off faces if you’d like? 

Seriously buy some self tanning drops for your usual moisturiser and some decent suncream for your holiday 

And a big hat and shades

@theveindoc @MarkGaze @frozenwarning I will agree however when it comes to the most dangerous thing most women ever do, and the thing with a huge list of morbities (for both methods of birth) I think a choice is important. 

And so does NICE and the high court. 

This argument has already been won.

@theveindoc @MarkGaze @frozenwarning My dad was offered a choice of ankle replacement or fusion. 

Why shouldn’t women be offered a choice of how to give birth? 

There is important case law surrounding this.

@MedicWeary @hayleymagill Hi, surgeon here. I’ll do LMA teeth (or chair side no tube for Paeds if the anaesthetist is happy) 

I suggested it frequently and was looked at like I had six heads in some places. 

If trainees not doing 14 cases then it’ll take twice as long to build up speed too.

@DrHFRyan @SteelCity_ENT @otorhinosaurus @DrJohnCosgrove I read the books by Emily Oster religiously. 

She’s wonderful critical appraisal and breaking it down to what’s necessary. 

I recommend them to everyone!!

@tryingtobeaDr @Veloskitty Plus if people are under occupied at work it becomes incredibly dull and soul destroying. 

And a shadow rota wouldn’t have helped in this case as it was only half an hour. 

Plus shadow Rotas are evil at the best of times.

@tryingtobeaDr Sorry I was a bit quick off the mark. 
I don’t think you can MAKE the SHO stay but they should. 
Also this would technically fall under prospective cover arrangements I think so contractually the SHO is obliged to stay.

@sortmyspine @RoshanaMN @OrthopodReg @parthaskar @StressHoop In the same scenario, in your life who would be sorting the problem? 

What were your Plans B, C and D and if they failed what was the likelihood of you having to leave work on time? Did you have another person to do this? 

If you did = privilege

@Ljpengels My life is so simple in comparison. 
Pointy thing, hot thing, grabby things. 

Not enough toys to need labels.

@cloudy_lemonade I’ve read all sorts, not usually fantasy… 
Strong female lead sounds good. I read fast (like 7 books in a 7 day beach holiday fast) 

I like the sound of just one damn thing after another!

@MikeGatMe Yeah lives alone, stairlift for getting up the stairs that she mostly refuses to use. Independent washing, cooking and dressing. 
Would still be driving if it wasn’t for the fact that she kept reversing into the gatepost! 
Someone took a good history from her.

@SandipP64097927 @ammanibash So where does it stop? How much unpaid work is acceptable? 

Note a TTO is not going to kill a patient, it’s not managing a clinical emergency. 

If a ward team can’t get the work done in the paid time, you need more ward staff- an exception report highlights this.

@ShakMustafa Totally, but this is about NTN’s and numbers of OMFS consultants. 
A singly qualified SAS isn’t an OMFS consultant. 

If we were talking about CESR for Oral Surgeons then absolutely I’m 100% behind you.

@BarkerFeet So if a dentist says that it may represent something slightly different. 

In a dental practice you usually work with 1 nurse everyday. 

The nurse will refer to ‘my dentist’ ‘our lab work’ ‘my patient list’

@OrthoWomen I’ve read this twice, and now for the third time. 

I’m sorry this was the email he chose to send to you to congratulate you on a consultant job. 

As for the rest, what a knob.

@thegradmedic Oh for heavens sake, professionalism points? 

Take your cue from the person you’re talking to as your friend did

As a fellow graduate medic I’d be scathing of a 23 Yr old F1 demanding I call them Dr, unless they’d correctly use my Dr title in return. (Dentist- @ medschool)

@CherylLeeAssoc @Trisha_the_doc Yeah, I have a vivid memory of a canoeing trip at school and a badly timed period. 

12 hours ‘on the water’ was not the easiest. 

Being a teenager was tough in retrospect.

@OrthoWomen @jamestoml1 @OrthoDiversity @WomenSurgeonsUK @BOTA_WinS @women_ortho I’ve always thought that this is potentially a golden opportunity for anaesethetics to prioritise. 

They’re the only ones who assess everyone, and know if the gen surg patient is actually septic or not. 

(NB will not work for neuro, they need locking in a box)

@drsas27 No it’s the le fort fracture, I wouldn’t want to do that on an oral tube. 

But there’s probably something that I’m missing. 

It is a very good distraction from revision though!

@theveindoc @AkbaniUmair @dan26wales So what is PT and what is FT? 
What about those who work solely privately? 
Why shouldn’t people pay for the children who will look after them in their old age? Both potentially as their doctors and to pay for their pension.

@trentconsultant @theveindoc @AkbaniUmair @dan26wales And therefore don’t contribute taxes but still cost society in old age. 
2 people working LTFT &gt; 1 working FT 

Especially since many LTFT aren’t always going to be that way and may well have periods of FT work within a long career.

@surashsurash @MarvelStudios Oh and boy doesn’t the entire world know it! 

#huganeurosurgeon  
#superheros

@iangordon1959 It was pretty bad in hospitals in March 2020, I think if we’d relaxed more more would have died. 

The question overall is what death/who’s death will we accept to keep the economy going. 

I don’t have an answer for that one.

@theveindoc @DrBaggins1 @EverydaySexism Not to mention that you’re telling me that my experience isn’t correct: that I’ve not heard these things? 
These are all in the last 2 months for heavens sake. 

Misogyny is rife in the UK.

@theveindoc @DrBaggins1 @EverydaySexism Older woman with 4 children 

‘You do know it’s a myth that women can have it all’ 

Has anyone EVER said that to Miran?

@theveindoc @DrBaggins1 @EverydaySexism 4 weeks ago: 
Senior consultant surgeon: 
Well obviously if you want to be an oncology surgeon you’ll have to think carefully about fellowships, and you can’t have a family

@theveindoc @DrBaggins1 @EverydaySexism Today: 
Me: Hello I’m Alex the facial surgery registrar on call….. explains post op instructions….. how to minimise scarring etc etc 
Parent: Thankyou Nurse, does the doctor have to come see us before we can go home?

@theveindoc @TurtonsOther @SteelCity_ENT @AbdoPainHotline In my experience it has nothing to do with working time- which many doctors actually don’t care about and to help out a colleague will gladly breach. 

The problem is that Rotas are too tight. 

Currently I’m 1in3

@hammond_douglas @MHA_92_ There is some of that- is the test actually needed. But the volume of admissions is also higher than it ever was. 
Just look at the year on year increases. 

For our speciality there’s probably no need for a phleb service; for a medical ward there really can be.

@helen_barnowl @SteelCity_ENT I’m not, I have worked with many ANP’s. 

Who do you ask for advice from when something is too complex? I ask the consultant, they may ask a more senior consultant. 

Decisions move upwards- I don’t have a problem with saying I see less complex stuff than the boss. Why do you?

@RamminaY @DrZeshanQureshi I had this ‘you’ve not signed up to any locums’ 

My response; what’s my second name and what specialty do I want to do? 

Maxfac isn’t that common! If I’m a number on a spreadsheet, expect me to behave like one!

@ShakMustafa @jtg_baoms Plastics ENT (6 months) Gen Surg. 

But honestly very dependent on placement- spending the entire time on ward cover isn’t exactly great. 
I am assuming everyone will have done a year of OMFS with that though

@DrUmeshPrabhu @Rebeccasmt @EPUTNHS So with regards to this, who would you hold to account? Because the easy target is a doctor or low level manager. 

We all know that these things are often systems based not individual. 

(I say this with zero knowledge of the case)

@whiterose_lady @theveindoc @Mx_Mischief @DeanEggitt @DrSimonHodes @DrSelvarajah So true. 

The upshot of this interesting thread is that we need to be more educated about money not less. 

And that pulling up the ladder behind you is a dick move.

@theveindoc @richtaylor93 @whiterose_lady @Mx_Mischief @DeanEggitt @DrSimonHodes @DrSelvarajah You don’t get to ‘choose’ how fast you repay (paying off additional amounts is traumatic due to the system) 

Yes there comes a point where borrowing more actually doesn’t matter because it just means more is written off. 

For now.... the rules can change and have before.

@trentconsultant @PhyllBuc @OrthopaedicOz @Dr_KM_ To be blunt; that’s not exactly new then. 

Students have always worked to fund their studies, many as HCA’s. 
unless they get credit for it what’s the point. They may as well just work the night shift; do the day at uni and finish quicker.

@WelshGasDoc Gah, i am so sick of this ‘real learning only happens on the wards schtick’

I was on the wards faking being a doctor for 4 years- I was no closer to actually being one until I went to medical school. 

You cannot learn the ‘real medicine’ until you have the foundations.

@Dr_KM_ I did a non traditional route to medicine (dental degree, worked then 3 years of med school whilst working my arse of nights, weekends, off days) 

I absolutely think things should be changed to make it easier/more flexible. 

But it should still be a degree level course.

@nik_henderson Once we start including hobbies, the normal thing to do is then to rank them. So 
team sport&gt;running&gt;chess&gt;Netflix

And then hobbies become something we need to have because we need a job, and by extension they become work and we need a new hobby.

@iwanttobeamedic This was my entire med school experience. 

Medical students en masse are the sort of people I probably tried hard to avoid. 

But I’m ok now I’m actually working.

@doctor_oxford I have no problem wearing a bin bag, a plastic apron isn’t really much different to a bin bag. 
Who the hell was using sanitary towels and why? 

I agree with your sentiment but I disagree with the rhetoric you’re using.

@Dr_Rach_P @DrLindaDykes Can you change your email settings to ‘fetch’ not ‘push’ 
That way you aren’t notified about email stuff until a time when you, being very disciplined, choose to check. 
Similarly can you set aside an amount of time (and set a timer) when you will do work &amp; stop when it’s done.

@ZaherToumi @DrSdeG @Jacquelin_Joyce Less than elective hips or less than all hips?? We know that a NoF is a different beast to an elective THR. 

What about the psychology input in bariatrics? The life long supplements some need? 

I think we should do more, lots more. But I don’t think your comparison is accurate

@O2 disgraceful service, i have been trying to move my old number onto your network for 3 weeks and it hasn’t happened yet. I have put in 6 online requests and 2 through your My O2 app. 
You’ve just cut me off when I’ve tried to call to speak to someone. 
Not good enough!

@orthohand The private is often subsidising the NHS. 
Not every treatment is available on the NHS but patients want to have treatment from their regular dentist. 
The dentist was only offered a tiny NHS contract so to make it viable they also offer Private. Many many reasons.

@feline_charm @MichJak @DrrBoz @BrennanSurgeon Erm yes, sadly i have said ‘bye thanks love you’ at the end of a telephone call to a radiology consultant. 

It doesn’t bother me to be called love, or ducky, or any of the above. 

I’m more bothered if they say ‘no offence love but I want a male dr’

@isabelguyrn Day 1. Find out when and how you are going to take your annual leave. 
Day 2. Submit your annual leave forms. 

As for the rest; you’ll be fine.

@hayleymagill Surely it depends on if your social media is purely work based or a mix. 

If purely for work then using your honorary title is reasonable. 

Now if you’d said don’t use it on your personal credit cards I’d have agreed with you.
